You’re close. The main issue is the **right image is too high/too zoomed vertically**, and the **left content is too high/small compared to Figma**.

Make these changes only.

## CSS fixes

```css
.page-header {
    height: 96px;
    padding: 16px 112px;
}

.content-container {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 600px;
    min-height: calc(100vh - 96px);
    align-items: start;
}

.left-content {
    padding-left: 112px;
    padding-top: 96px;
    padding-right: 80px;
    max-width: 720px;
}

.left-content h1 {
    font-size: 48px;
    line-height: 1.15;
}

.left-content h2 {
    font-size: 40px;
}

.right-illustration {
    position: relative;
    width: 600px;
    height: 804px;
    margin-top: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    border-top-left-radius: 40px;
    background: #154734;
}

.background-pattern {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    z-index: 1;
}

.mascot {
    position: absolute;
    width: 610px;
    right: -120px;
    bottom: -70px;
    z-index: 2;
}
```

Your current mascot is cut at the head because `bottom` is too low/negative and width is too large. This version brings it down to roughly “head to knees” like Figma.

If it still shows too much leg, use:

```css
.mascot {
    width: 660px;
    right: -140px;
    bottom: -120px;
}
```

